    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Central Park Terror: The Outcry</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>NOW Legal Defense and Education Fund senior staff attorney Julie Goldscheid letter says nothing more clearly demonstrates that women are still targets of violence just because of their gender than mob attack in Central Park</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Nothing more clearly demonstrates that women are still targets of violence just because of our gender than last weekend's mob attack in Central Park (front page, June 13).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Nothing more clearly demonstrates that women are still targets of violence just because of our gender than last weekend's mob attack in Central Park (front page, June 13).</p>
        <p>In 1994, Congress enacted the Violence Against Women Act, which provided substantial financing to communities across the country to help the police better address this problem.  But the law expires this year, and Congress is sitting on its hands, refusing to reauthorize these programs and letting proposals languish that would allow the Justice Department to prosecute gender-based hate crimes like these.</p>
        <p>Despite the tremendous progress we've made, last weekend's terror shows that we still have a long way to go.</p>
        <p>JULIE GOLDSCHEID  Senior Staff Atty., NOW Legal  Defense and Education Fund  New York, June 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
